│ the Issue:\nThe crash occurs in ConstantRangeList::insert due to an assertion │
│ that the inserted ConstantRange must have a strictly increasing signed        │
│ interval: NewRange.getLower().slt(NewRange.getUpper()). In the reproducer, a  │
│ huge GEP offset close to INT64_MAX is used, and code in function-attrs        │
│ computes an access range by adding the type size or length to that offset     │
│ using signed 64-bit APInt. When the sum overflows signed 64-bit, APInt wraps  │
│ modulo 2^64, and the constructed ConstantRange ends up with lower >= upper in │
│ signed terms, violating the assertion.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe        │
│ debug-only output shows the assertion in ConstantRangeList::insert is hit     │
│ immediately when function-attrs starts. The backtrace points to               │
│ getArgumentAccessInfo at FunctionAttrs.cpp:689 (within the                    │
│ GetTypeAccessRange/GetConstantIntRange logic), then                           │
│ collectArgumentUsesPerBlock, inferInitializes, addArgumentAttrs. That matches │
│ the code paths that construct ConstantRange([offset, offset+size)). The       │
│ insertion happens early, confirming the issue arises from computing access    │
│ ranges for a store.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nIn getArgumentAccessInfo, the │
│ helpers GetTypeAccessRange and GetConstantIntRange construct                  │
│ ConstantRange(APInt(64, *Offset, true), APInt(64, *Offset + Size, true)). The │
│ addition \"*Offset + Size\" is performed in signed 64-bit domain without      │
│ overflow checks. For Offset = 9223372036854775804 and Size = 4, the sum is    │
│ 9223372036854775808, which is out of range for int64_t and wraps to           │
│ -9223372036854775808 when cast back to signed 64-bit. APInt(64, value, true)  │
│ builds signed values, thus we get Lower = INT64_MAX-? and Upper = INT64_MIN,  │
│ causing Lower.slt(Upper) to be false, triggering the assertion when inserting │
│ into ConstantRangeList. This is not a bug in ConstantRangeList; it correctly  │
│ asserts preconditions. The bug is in function-attrs: it must avoid            │
│ constructing invalid ranges on overflow.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nWe    │
│ need to add overflow checks before constructing ConstantRange in both helpers │
│ and the Initializes attribute path. If the addition would overflow signed     │
│ 64-bit, fall back to conservatively returning std::nullopt or an empty range, │
│ so we do not insert invalid ranges.\n\n- Edit Point 1 (lines 661-678 in       │
│ FunctionAttrs.cpp): Wrap GetTypeAccessRange and GetConstantIntRange           │
│ computations with checks that ensure *Offset + Size (or +Length) does not     │
│ overflow int64_t, and that lower < upper in signed sense. Use int64_t range   │
│ limits to guard. If the check fails, return std::nullopt.\nSuggested change   │
│ outline:\n  * In GetTypeAccessRange: after computing Size, check if *Offset   │
│ >= 0 and Size > 0 and *Offset <= std::numeric_limits<int64_t>::max() - Size.  │
│ If not, return std::nullopt. Then construct APInt for lower and upper.\n  *   │
│ In GetConstantIntRange: obtain len = ConstantLength->getSExtValue(), ensure   │
│ len > 0 and Offset present, and check *Offset <= INT64_MAX - len. If check    │
│ fails, return std::nullopt. Then construct APInt lower/upper.\n\n- Edit Point │
│ 2 (lines 736-741 in FunctionAttrs.cpp): In the Initializes case, when         │
│ applying the offset to each ConstantRange from the attribute, ensure the      │
│ addition of ArgUse.Offset to CR.getLower()/getUpper() does not overflow. If   │
│ it would overflow, skip inserting that range (or, more conservatively, clear  │
│ AccessRanges to avoid any invalid range). For simplicity and safety, if any   │
│ range overflows, do not insert it; the overall access info can still be       │
│ considered a write but with empty ranges.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy adding signed │
│ overflow checks before constructing ConstantRange objects and when shifting   │
│ ranges by ArgUse.Offset, we prevent invalid intervals from being created.     │
│ This avoids triggering the ConstantRangeList assertion while maintaining      │
│ conservative correctness: when an access range cannot be represented safely,  │
│ we treat it as unknown/empty, which errs on the side of not deriving overly   │
│ strong attributes. The fix ensures function-attrs no longer crashes on large  │
│ pointer offsets that exceed int64_t bounds."})                                │
